The Civil Society Legislative Advocacy Centre (CISLAC) has felicitated with the 9th National Assembly (NASS) on its first year in steering the wheel of the national legislative affairs. CISLAC, in a statement signed by its executive director, Auwal Ibrahim Musa (Rafsanjani), acknowledged various initiatives by the legislature such as the return of budget cycle to January-December to ensure timely release of funds and cash-backing for the development of ailing critical sectors and the Finance Bill, 2019,  (now Finance Act) assented by President Muhammadu Buhari to support the implementation of the 2020 budget and to create an enabling environment for businesses. The group also listed; Deep Offshore and Inland Basin Production Sharing Contracts Act Amendment Bill (the Act) to ensure that the production sharing contract is economically beneficial to the government of the federation and the passage of Emergency Stimulus Bill, 2020, as a response to the COVID-19 pandemic to mitigate impact on businesses and individuals in Nigeria.” CISLAC  also commended the sustained open-door policy by the legislature for civil Society legislative engagement, just as it applauded the recent mainstreaming of information technology in technical proceedings in the legislative rules and protocols , aimed at enhancing  the legislative process and citizen participation in legislative activities in the face of COVID-19 pandemic era. The group also noted the oversight activities by various Legislative Committees of the National Assembly, including those targeted at appropriations and blocking of financial leakages across Ministries, Departments and Agencies (MDAs) as well as persistent probes of alleged fraud and mismanagement of funds and flouting of Federal Character Act across MDAs. They however, drew the attention of the legislature to other areas of priority which according to them awaited significant improvement, as it steps into another legislative year.